                    <floatingText>
                        <body>
                            <div type="poem">
                                <lg>
                                    <l>So rose the scene [of <placeName corresp="#SPOLETO">Spoleto</placeName>] on <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName>&#x02BC; classic eye</l>
                                    <l>And thus, embalmed in words that ne&#x02BC;er could die,</l>
                                    <l>Its touching image had remained enshrined,</l>
                                    <l>Had <hi rend="italic">he</hi> to verse transferred it from his mind.</l>
                                    <l>Far other fate awaits this rustic lay,</l>
                                    <l>Framed for the passing purpose of a day:</l>
                                    <l>Enough for me if he its tone commend</l>
                                    <l>Whom &#x02BC;tis a pride and grace to call my Friend.</l>
                                </lg>
                                <lb/>
                                <p>(<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#FRIENDSHIPSOFFERING1830"><title type="annual" corresp="#FRIENDSHIPSOFFERING1830"><hi rend="italic">Friendship&#x02BC;s Offering; A Literary Album . . . for MDCCCXXX</hi></title></ref>, 111).</p>
                            </div>
                        </body>
                    </floatingText>
                    <p>Lines from <persName corresp="#TP">Pringle</persName>&#x02BC;s &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#PRINGLESPOLETO">Spoleto</title>&#x201D; are possibly echoed by <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> in &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRSALTZBURG">Saltzburg</title>&#x201D;.</p>
                    <p>The extract first highlights the town&#x02BC;s fame for repulsing an attack by <persName corresp="#HANNIBAL">Hannibal</persName>&#x02BC;s army, following the Cathaginian victory over <placeName corresp="#ROME">Rome</placeName>, a continuing source of local pride which is mentioned in all guidebooks. 
                        The passage then scans the town&#x02BC;s major monuments, using a strategy that may have been instructive to <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>. As a Roman Catholic priest, 
                        <persName corresp="#JCEUSTACE">Eustace</persName> dwells on the Gothic cathedral, of course admiring its beauty in contrast with lighting its lurid fascination as <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> does; 
                        however, the passage also presents views of the cathedral that are invisible in the plate, such as details from its interior, 
                        and the prospect looking outward from its terrace. This accidental juxtaposition of conflicting viewpoints may have given; the &#x201C;barbarous antiquity&#x201D; of its castle 
                        (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#EUSTACECLASSICALTOUR">see <persName corresp="#JCEUSTACE">Eustace</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#EUSTACECLASSICALTOUR"><hi rend="italic">A Classical Tour through Italy</hi></title>,</ref> 1:177&#x2013;79). </p>
                    <p>Forsyth 3d ed, 1824, 2:94; Lalande 6:247&#x2013;50</p>
